The fluorescence peak of synthesized BST was recorded at emission wavelength 818 nm (Fig. 4
                        ). For sensing experiment, stock solution (600 μM) of metal ions was prepared in milipore water. The metal ion solution was then mixed with a BST suspension (100 ppm) by 1:1 (vol/vol) and ultrasonicated for 10 s to equilibrate them. Investigations were done for evaluating the ability of monovalent, divalent and trivalent metal ion to quench the fluorescence of BST NPs. The monovalent metal ions viz NH4
                        +, Cu+, K+, divalent metal ions viz Cd2+, Ba2+, Cu2+, Sn2+, Pd2+, Hg2+, Ni2+, Mn2+, Zn2+, Sb2+, Fe2+ and trivalent metal ions Cr3+, Fe3+ and Al3+ were selected for sensing experiment. The high sensing ability for Fe3+ ion (Fig. 5
                        ) clearly revealed the fluorescence quenching efficiency for the Fe3+ ion was of greater extent of all the 18 studied metal ions. The relative high quenching of fluorescence intensity by the Fe3+ ion is exceptionally high as compared to other metal ions which clearly demonstrated that the highly sensible property of BST for Fe3+ ion. These results assured the excellent selectivity of synthesized BST nanoparticles towards Fe3+ ion.

The fluorescence response of BST/Fe3+ system in the presence of other metal ion such as Cd2+, Ba2+, Cu2+, Sn2+, Pb2+, NH4
                        +, Na+, K+, Fe2+ and Mn2+ was investigated in order to explore their interference. The no effect on the fluorescence intensity of BST NPs/Fe3+ was recorded. BST NPs fluoresence sensor can be used to distinguish the different oxidation state of iron (Fig. 10
                        )
